his redesigned self by advancing fresh readings of texts by William Shakespeare, Christopher Marlowe, John Webster, and Margaret Cavendish. The eco-self offers certain refinements to ecological theory by renewing appreciation for the rational, deliberative functions that distinguish humans from other species.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 0aEcocriticism. 0aEnglish literatureyEarly modern, 1500-1700xHistory and criticism. 0aNature in literature. 4aEarly Modern Studies. 4aEnvironment and Sustainability. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 4aLiterary Theory, Criticism, and History. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Shakespeare.2bisacsh  aEarly Modern Ecocriticism, Ecopsychology, Early Modern Identity or Personhood, Eco-Self or Ecological Self.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311102374840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9789048556946?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789048556946423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789048556946/original  a978-3-11-102374-8  Amsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK